            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="de">J G Agardh</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 10pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">Lund Sweden 7 August 88.<seg style="font-size: 6.5pt; "> </seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 10pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Highly esteemed Baron!</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 10pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>When your last of 1 June 1888 arrived at the beginning of July I was already in the country — living in the neighbourhood of Lund, where I am accustomed to spend the summer months of recent years; and it was not possible for me to investigate the algae gathered from Israelite Bay by Miss Brooks immediately. However, afterwards I have had the opportunity to be able to scrutinize the algae more closely, and today I am sending you a list of them. There are some strange forms among them — one uncommonly thick branched <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                  <name key="Wrangelia%20myriophylloides">Wrangelia myriophylloides</name>
               </seg> that I have never seen previously — but hardly think that any new species should be hiding among them, although previously I have had several rarities from Israelite Bay and particularly several fragments of Sargassae, which however were too poor to be determined more exactly.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 10pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Previously I believe I have turned your attention already to how desirable it would be to have complete specimens of the especially rich Sargassae-flora of Australia. The same species looks quite different, if one just has the <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">lower</hi>
               </seg> or just the <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">upper</hi>
               </seg> plant before one, so also the <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">sterile</hi>
               </seg> and <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">fertile</hi>
               </seg>. For years I worked to get to know all these different forms more exactly; and I would like to ask you once again to ask your correspondents to be willing to send me whole specimens (unprepared). I am certain I will do much better thereby than through the collections of Florideae that so very often only bring the same things. It is surprising how little our first algologists knew of the Sargassae!</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; font-size: 10pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Most devotedly signs</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; font-size: 10pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>J. G. Agardh</p>
